			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Without a shadow of a doubt, I am utterly certain that Rytan and the boys are listening to us and duly weighing our concerns. The March 25th patch will go down in mage history as one of the Fabled Great Patches to accompany the melee upgrade patch we received last year.
<br />

<br />
The mitigation change was a good start, nay a fantastic start. But it is not the cure to what ails us.
<br />

<br />
Mages suffer in the scalability of their DPS, this is because their pets scarcely operate as more than a speed bump in tier 3/4/5 encounters. As a matter of fact, off the top of my head, I can name no less than five raid-level encounters where keeping a pet alive is both inefficient AND difficult.
<br />

<br />
-Solusek Ro
<br />
-Grioidihr the Wise
<br />
-Tallon Zek
<br />
-Rydda'dar
<br />
-Aerin'dar
<br />

<br />
A mage will instantly lose 60-80 DPS from their pet when they fall in battle.
<br />

<br />
The mitigation changes will serve to reduce the melee damage taken, but it's of little to no worth when the pet isn't dying from melee. Indeed, the soloers are probably quite pleased with their upgrade, but I am not satisfied. Nor, I expect, is a large portion of the raiding mage populace.
<br />

<br />
They know what kills their pet. And they know that an increase in melee damage mitigation is not going to solve the rapid death of their pet.
<br />

<br />
Pets, despite calliav and the use of their master's resistances, are still far too susceptible to non-melee damage for their own good, and ours.
<br />

<br />
And even with superior mitigation via melee, the ailing mage DPS at the tier 4/5 level has <b>not been remedied</b>, and this is the quality I believe we need the most.
<br />

<br />
Even with the mitigation changes, initial testing has proven the changes impotent to fully address the mitigation concerns we have. Ylaine's parsing, and Xalmat's subsequent analysis concludes that pet mitigation is now roughly that of a Cleric.
<br />

<br />
As Itchyban put it: "When's the last time you used a spare Cleric to off tank?"
<br />

<br />
Indeed this statement is so ridiculously adequate to describe the understated conclusion to the overstated introduction of our "Pet upgrades" that I am amused by the mere simplicity with which Itchyban has summarized our new, and scarcely changed, state of affairs.
<br />

<br />
I am pleased with the mitigation upgrades, but I say, and with just cause:
<br />

<br />
<b>These changes are not enough. A pet tanking like a cleric is unacceptable, dying in 10 seconds is unacceptable, and not dealing damage so as to adequately provide a consistent and sizeable portion of the magician's offensive output is <i><u>unacceptable</i></u></b><br />_________________<br />working on a new sig.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Qaedain Magi'kot on Fri Mar 26, 2004 9:44 pm; edited 2 times in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
