			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ignoring the non-sequetors, I agree with the lead post.
<br />

<br />
The cost to maintain a pet still outweighs its incremental value over pure casting or pure melee DPS in most non-XP settings. This includes either time or mana, depending on the battle, to Callaiv, heal, and/or cure the pets, on top of that required for the mage. This time/mana comes not only from the mage, but the rest of the party, making mages "high-maintenance" compared to other DPS classes providing better DPS and arguably more utility.
<br />

<br />
Note that neither a wizard nor a rogue have to reduce their DPS to stay alive in an AoE situation.
<br />

<br />
Callaiv is not a good solution as takes one "casting window" to refresh on the pet. That is a loss of about 2000 damage right there. With a pet only doing 60 DPS, I'm better off letting it die if the mob isn't going to be up longer than another 45 seconds (which gets less likely with raid mobs dropping in typically three minutes or less).
<br />

<br />
The raves about pet improvements have come mainly from those who regularly use Rathe's Son to tank in solo or non-conventional groups.
<br />

<br />
There is still virtually no scaling past DPoC for mages' focii.
<br />

<br />
The pets are still inadequate in their abilities to reduce damage uptake and the heals are still inadequate to deal with damage uptake, even if further improvements are made to the pets.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.sovereignguild.org/forum/viewtopic.php?t=4429" target="_blank" class="postlink">Sage Itchyban of Veeshan</a></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by itchyban on Fri Mar 26, 2004 6:30 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
